<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/46369814-ibn-yosf"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1500958052i/46369814._UX100_CR0,18,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/46369814-ibn-yosf">ibN YoSF</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    It’s not really about who would sit and sob after you depart, it’s about what could prompt anyone to even think of you when you depart. Technically, i<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    It’s not really about who would sit and sob after you depart, it’s about what could prompt anyone to even think of you when you depart. Technically, it need not be of any concern to you, nevertheless like a funny phrase goes ‘No one has ever complained about a dysfunctional parachute’, no one has ever came back neither to complain nor to praise of anything they left behind. <br /><br />In a nutshell, the book is indeed about living your life to every atom of it. With all due respect, let me finish up with this, If someone even cares to remember how you lost, surely everyone will care to remember your legacy or triumph!<br /><a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
