<span id="freeTextContainer4088446691489506715">I bought this book too; it&apos;s at home, somewhere, collecting dust. I&apos;d never read it, though. How can you one star a book without reading it, you ask. I hate it when authors use the success of their previous book to sell new books. And I don&apos;t mean like sequels here. I&apos;m referring to how E.L. James wrote the same fucking book from his point of view, and that became a best seller too. Or Ravinder Singh, who, while banking on the success of his first book, referred to it more times than I could cou</span>
  <span id="freeText4088446691489506715" style="display:none">I bought this book too; it's at home, somewhere, collecting dust. I'd never read it, though. How can you one star a book without reading it, you ask. I hate it when authors use the success of their previous book to sell new books. And I don't mean like sequels here. I'm referring to how E.L. James wrote the same fucking book from his point of view, and that became a best seller too. Or Ravinder Singh, who, while banking on the success of his first book, referred to it more times than I could count in his second book, to sell it. Sharma here does the same, and nope. Just nope. <br /><br />P.S. What does does it mean that all of the books that I've referred to above are shit books? *shrugs*</span>
