<div id="review_3139927652" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3139927652" />
    <a title="Muskan | The Quirky Reader" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/83049814-muskan-the-quirky-reader"><img alt="Muskan | The Quirky Reader" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1563800749p2/83049814.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3139927652?book_show_action=true">Jan 20, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Muskan | The Quirky Reader" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Muskan | The Quirky Reader" href="/user/show/83049814-muskan-the-quirky-reader">Muskan | The Quirky Reader</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3139927652" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15559086896578574801"><br/>I am not a huge fan of non-fiction, but starting with 2020, I vowed to try to read at least one non-fic book a month, starting with this one.<br/>From what I understand, this book is the 3rd part of the “monk who sold his Ferrari” series, but can be read as a stand alone too. <br/>It is a tiny book, with tiny length of lessons that portray huge ideas, The common factor among all the lessons? Just make your time worth it!<br/>I found some amazing lessons in the book, which I will definitely be using in my life.</span>
  <span id="freeText15559086896578574801" style="display:none"><br />I am not a huge fan of non-fiction, but starting with 2020, I vowed to try to read at least one non-fic book a month, starting with this one.<br />From what I understand, this book is the 3rd part of the “monk who sold his Ferrari” series, but can be read as a stand alone too. <br />It is a tiny book, with tiny length of lessons that portray huge ideas, The common factor among all the lessons? Just make your time worth it!<br />I found some amazing lessons in the book, which I will definitely be using in my life. However, I found a few of them, in the real world, away from paper, would contradict each other. So I guess one of the unwritten lessons would be “you can’t have everything and must decide”. While some suggestions like taking worry breaks, working on public speaking, writing thank-you notes etc were truly inspiring and have somewhat already been adapted in my daily schedule, some suggestions appeared unrealistic to me. It may differ from person to person, of course.<br />What I specifically liked a lot about the book was that it offered real solutions. When it said “you should work on public speaking”, it answered the why, how, and what after as well. There are a lot of quotations and references of various personalities that held the most inspiring thoughts of the book.<br />It has also changed my perspective of self-help books. I used to think that these books are for people who need positivity in life or some sort of help. But it is also for those who need the simple motivation to be better everyday than you were yesterday. <br />I really liked the book, and I suggest you to read it as well.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15559086896578574801" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

